Here's how to implement all three:

**1. Custom "Cancel" back button** — in `EditProductPage.xaml`:

```xml
<ContentPage ...>
    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding BackCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
    <!-- page content -->
</ContentPage>
```

**2. Navigation guard with confirmation dialog** — in `AppShell.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    if (args.Source == ShellNavigationSource.Pop
        && Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.CurrentPage
            .DisplayAlert("Unsaved Changes",
                           "Discard changes?",
                           "Discard", "Stay");
        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();

        deferral.Complete();
    }
}
```

**3. ViewModel back command** — triggers the same guard:

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    private bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    private async Task Back()
    {
        // GoToAsync("..") fires OnNavigating, so the guard runs automatically
        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

**Key points:**
- `GetDeferral()` is required because `DisplayAlert` is async — without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- `args.Cancel()` must be called before `deferral.Complete()`.
- The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` routes through `GoToAsync("..")`, which triggers the same `OnNavigating` guard — one guard handles both the custom button and the system back gesture.
